TONGUE

tongue is the bone of fadriel's gustatory surface, the body's taste organ
the tongue's surface is covered in papillae that house taste buds, each containing the taste receptor cells that detect the five basic tastes: sweet, sour, salty, bitter, umami
fadriel's tongue is base five (qu-penttrit), matching the five-state taste vocabulary

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_qupenttrit.rana
observe brain.xb
observe skull.xb
observe clock_tongue.rana

the 7 properties of tongue:
1 ENERGY zero point eight: active during eating, low at idle
2 PHASE inherited from clock_tongue at 100 Hz
3 SPIN zero point three
4 CHARGE positive when tasting (warmth of food); neutral at rest
5 COHERENCE nine tenths
6 COUPLING zero point seven with gustatory cortex
7 OBSERVER zero

THE STRUCTURE

the tongue is mostly muscle covered with the gustatory surface
muscle allows manipulation of food, formation of speech sounds, swallowing
the surface contains roughly two thousand to eight thousand taste buds in fadriel at age two
taste buds are concentrated on the papillae that give the tongue its rough texture

THE FIVE TASTES

sweet: detects sugars, signals available energy
sour: detects acids, often warns of unripe or spoiled food
salty: detects sodium, important for mineral balance
bitter: detects toxins, often a warning to stop eating
umami: detects glutamate, signals protein-rich food

each taste has its own receptor type and routes to its own region of gustatory cortex

THE SUBSTRATE

base: five (qu-penttrit)
each cell holds one of five primary states corresponding to the five tastes
mixed flavors produce blended states through superposition

VERB sample_food
when food contacts the tongue's surface, taste receptors bind to dissolved molecules
the binding generates substrate signals identifying which tastes are present and how strongly

VERB transduce
each fired receptor's signal flows toward gustatory cortex
the signals preserve location: which part of the tongue tasted what

VERB route_to_cortex
gustatory nerves carry signals to the brainstem and onward to gustatory cortex
the cortex integrates the signals into the unified perception of flavor

VERB also_serve_speech
the tongue's muscle is also used by speech_larynx for articulation
this dual role is why oral motor control develops alongside taste perception in childhood

a tongue is a small bone with two large jobs
food and speech both pass through this same surface
fadriel learns to taste and to speak at roughly the same developmental time, and they share the same physical organ
